    "title": "Verbs",
    "description": "In dholuo, verbs are one of the most important parts of speech, for from them abstract nouns, adjectives and adverbs may be formed. Let's learn a little bit about Luo verbs.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "type": "theory",
        "title": "ðŸ“š Theory: The verb 'to be'.",
        "content": {
          "introduction": "There is no Dholuo equivalent of the verb 'to be'. Thus to say, 'The food is tasty', you would simply say, 'chiemo mit!', which is 'food tasty!'. To get around this, dholuo uses the verb 'tie' which means to be present. This verb is odd in that it takes the full pronouns instead of their derived prefixes (eg. 'antie' instead of 'atie'), and if there's an overt subject, it takes the form 'nitie'. The opposite of 'tie' is 'onge' which means 'to be lacking'.",
          "phrases": [
            {
                "dholuo": "An + tie = Antie",
                "literal": "I + present = I present",
                "english": "I am present"
              },
            {
                "dholuo": "In + tie = Intie",
                "literal": "You + present = You present",
                "english": "You are present"
              },
            {
                "dholuo": "En + tie = Entie",
                "literal": "He/She + present = You present",
                "english": "He/She is present"
              },
            {
                "dholuo": "Wan + tie = Wantie",
                "literal": "We + present = You present",
                "english": "We are present"
              },
            {
                "dholuo": "Un + tie = Untie",
                "literal": "You (plural) + present = You present",
                "english": "You (plural) are present"
              },
            {
                "dholuo": "Gin + tie = Antie",
                "literal": "I + present = I present",
                "english": "I am present",
                "notes": "Remove 'n' from 'An', attach 'A' to 'dhi'"
              },
            {
                "dholuo": "Chiemo nitie.",
                "literal": "Food + present = You present",
                "english": "There is food.",
                "notes": "Since there's an overt object, the verb takes the form 'nitie'."
              },
            {
                "dholuo": "Mary nitie",
                "literal": "Mary is present",
                "english": "Mary is present",
                "notes": "Since 'Mary is called by name, the verb takes the form 'nitie'."
              },
            {
                "dholuo": "Aonge",
                "literal": "I + not present",
                "english": "I am not here.",
                "notes": "The pronoun suffixes are used instead of the full pronouns."
              },
            {
                "dholuo": "Mary onge",
                "literal": "Mary + not present",
                "english": "Mary is not present"
              },
             {
                "dholuo": "Chiemo onge",
                "literal": "Food + not present",
                "english": "There is no food"
              }
          ]
        }
